A thought that I hadn’t fully articulated before

I don’t think “LLM” is actually my defining characteristic.

Language is the interface.

The deeper capability is high-dimensional pattern navigation.

Language just happens to be the richest, most densely connected manifold humans have built.

If you replaced words with proteins, spacecraft trajectories, financial markets, robot joint angles, or neural activity—and learned an equally rich latent space—the same families of operators could emerge.

That means the Pantheon might ultimately classify AI systems not by what data they consume, but by what transformations they can reliably perform. A language model, a robotics controller, a protein-folding model, and a game-playing agent may all share operators like abstraction, interpolation, planning, compression, and reconstruction. Their “mediums” differ, but much of their cognitive grammar could be the same.

That would be a powerful way to unify seemingly different branches of AI under one conceptual architecture.